\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 Then this cell grew a little and started to divide. First, it divided in two. However, here something happen\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 
ed that you would find very interesting: The information in the cell did not divide into two. That means the same information was duplicated in the two cells. After this, the cells continued to divide and the same information duplication happened in all o
\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 f\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  them, resulting in many cells with the same information. Then these were divided into others, and others divided into others. This event continued until millions of cells formed.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 While all this was happening, something you would never guess took place!
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 These cells, although they contain the same information, started doing tasks that are different from each other. Some of them formed your brother\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 
s skin. Some others formed his muscles, yet others his skeleton, and others his brain neurons.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 While the cells\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0  continued to multiply, the group of cells that was almost like a ball started to take shape. As you can see in the pictures at the top of the page, first your brother\hich\f0 \rquote 
\loch\f0 s head appeared, followed by his thin arms and then his legs. The cells continued to gr\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 o\hich\af0\dbch\af13\loch\f0 \hich\f0 
